---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const outputs = [
  ['Staging and marts', 'Clean, documented models that map directly to your source systems and business entities.'],
  ['Tests and lineage', 'Data quality assertions and column-level lineage with every model — whether you have these today or you are trying to get there.'],
  ['Real dbt in your repo', 'Standard dbt SQL your engineers can inspect, modify, and extend with or without SNADLY.'],
  ['Docs that stay current', 'Column descriptions, assumptions, and transformation logic that ship with the model rather than lagging behind.'],
];

const workflow = [
  ['1. SNADLY interprets a source system', 'Generates staging models, intermediate logic, marts, tests, and documentation in standard dbt SQL.'],
  ['2. A PR lands in your repo', 'Your analytics engineer reviews the pull request like any other contribution — comments, change requests, approval.'],
  ['3. Your team merges what passes review', 'Your governance. Your codebase. Your standards. Nothing ships without your sign-off.'],
  ['4. You own everything going forward', 'Modify any model with or without SNADLY. Hand it to a new hire. Move it to a different repo. It is just dbt.'],
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="SNADLY for BI teams"
  description="Get more dbt models into production without lowering the bar. Standard dbt PRs raised against your repo, reviewed and owned by your team."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">For BI teams</p>
    <h1>More models into production. Same team. Best practice by default.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Your team knows what good looks like. They are also drowning. SNADLY
      generates standard dbt models, tests, and docs — raises a PR against
      your repo — and your engineers decide what ships.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button" href="mailto:adrian.white@gmail.com">Book a PoC</a>
      <a class="button button-secondary" href="#how-it-works">How it works</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-muted split">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">The problem</p>
      <h2>Your team is so busy building they cannot govern.</h2>
      <p>
        The business asks for a dashboard. Your analytics engineer estimates 3
        weeks. Meanwhile, marketing has started building their own reports
        because BI is too slow — numbers now disagree across the company.
        Tests get skipped to hit deadlines. Documentation is 6 months behind.
        The warehouse works, but it is held together by one person's memory.
      </p>
      <p>
        The fastest path to better governance is taking the repeatable build
        work off your team so they have the bandwidth to review, test, and
        document at the standard they want.
      </p>
    </div>
    <aside class="note">
      <h3>Best fit</h3>
      <p>Teams with a real BI function who understand dbt best practice and are stretched too thin to stay there. If you know what tests you should be writing, SNADLY writes the first draft.</p>
      <h3>Your team still runs the show</h3>
      <p>SNADLY raises a PR. Your engineers review, request changes, and merge. You own every line. You can modify anything with or without SNADLY. Your governance, your codebase.</p>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="how-it-works">
    <p class="eyebrow">How it works with your team</p>
    <h2>Contributes like another team member.</h2>
    <div class="item-grid">
      {workflow.map(([title, text]) => (
        <article>
          <h3>{title}</h3>
          <p>{text}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-muted">
    <p class="eyebrow">What you get</p>
    <h2>Real dbt. Not dbt-style.</h2>
    <div class="item-grid">
      {outputs.map(([title, text]) => (
        <article>
          <h3>{title}</h3>
          <p>{text}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section split">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">No black box</p>
      <h2>Standard dbt SQL. No AI at runtime. Your engineers are the gate.</h2>
      <p>
        Models are generated once — after that, they are just dbt code in your
        repo. You can modify anything, move it anywhere, hand it to a new hire
        six months from now. Nothing depends on SNADLY being available.
      </p>
      <p>
        The AI writes the first draft. Your team reviews and owns the finished
        model. Governance is not automated away — it is given the room to
        actually happen.
      </p>
    </div>
    <aside class="note">
      <h3>Pricing that does not punish scale</h3>
      <p>Pricing follows the people who build and the pipelines that run — not the people who glance at a dashboard. Email reports and scheduled snapshots do not add to the bill. See the <a href="/pricing/">pricing page</a> for detail.</p>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section class="section cta">
    <p class="eyebrow">First step</p>
    <h2>We raise a PR. Your engineer reviews it.</h2>
    <p>SNADLY generates staging models, marts, tests, and docs for one of your real source systems. The output lands as a PR against a test repo. Your analytics engineer reviews it like any other contribution. If she would merge it, you have something worth scaling.</p>
    <a class="button" href="mailto:adrian.white@gmail.com">Book a PoC</a>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
